We made another fascinating observation: Normal stem cells are very active -- they divide very quickly.
They never die, they are immortal.
But these cells behaved differently.
They slowly divided and even died after a few weeks.
So we saw a new, strange cell population that looked like stem cells but behaved differently.
It took us a long time to understand where they came from.
They come from these cells.
These blue and red cells are called doublecortin positive cells.
We all have them in our brain.
They make up 4% of our cerebral cortex cells.
They play a very important role in our development.
In the fetal stage, they take care of the folding of the brain.
But why do they stay with us?
We do not know that.
We believe they are involved in brain healing as we find them in higher concentrations near brain injuries.
However, that is not so certain.
One thing is clear though -- from these cells we got our stem cells.
We are faced with a potential source of cells that enable brain healing.
We had to prove that.
So we decided to design an experiment.
We wanted to take a piece of non-linguistic brain matter and then culture the cells exactly as Jean-François did
and then color-code them to track them in the brain.
In the final step, we reimplanted them at the donor site of the same individual.
We call this autologous transplantation -- autotransplantation.
One of our first questions was: what happens if we reimplant these cells into normal brain tissue? And what will happen if we reimplant the same cells into damaged brain tissue?
Thanks to the help of Prof. Eric Rouiller, we were able to work with monkeys.
In the first scenario, we re-implanted the cells into a healthy brain and we observed that after a few weeks they completely disappeared, as if they had been removed, they go back home. The room is already occupied, they are not needed there, so they leave.
In the second scenario, we inflicted an injury and reimplanted the exact same cells, and now the cells stayed -- they grew into mature neurons.
Here you can see what we observed under the microscope.
These are the cells that have been reimplanted.
The proof they show is these little dots. These are the cells that we stained in vitro, in culture.
Of course we couldn&#39;t stop there.
Do these cells also help a monkey recover from a brain injury?
So we trained monkeys with a manual skill task.
They had to take feed pellets from a tray.
They did very well.
When they reached a stable level of dexterity, we injured the hand motor area in the motor cortex.
As a result, the monkeys were paralyzed and could no longer move their hands.
Just as would happen in humans, they spontaneously recovered to some degree, just like after a stroke.
The patients are paralyzed and then they try to recover with the help of plastic brain mechanisms. They recover to some degree, just like the monkey.
Once we were certain that the monkey had reached its level of spontaneous recovery, we implanted its own cells.
On the left you can see the monkey that spontaneously recovered.
He can perform about 40% to 50% of his original performance before the injury.
It&#39;s not as precise and not as fast.
Now look when we reimplanted the cells: The same monkey, two months after the reimplantation.
I can tell you that these were very exciting results for us too.
Since that time we have found out a great deal more about these cells.
We can freeze them and use them later.
We can use them in other neuropathological models, for example in Parkinson&#39;s.
But our dream is still to implant them in humans.
I really hope that soon I can show you how the human brain gives us the tools to heal itself.
Thanks very much.
