Democracy.
We in the West make a big mistake in taking them for granted.
We see democracy not as the fragile plant it really is, but as an inventory of our society.
We tend to think of them as an unchanging fact.
We believe that capitalism inevitably leads to democracy.
That&#39;s not true.
Lee Kuan Yew of Singapore and his great imitators in Beijing have proven beyond a doubt that it is entirely possible to have thriving capitalism and impressive growth while politics remain utterly undemocratic.
In fact, democracy is dwindling here, in Europe.
Earlier this year, when I represented Greece -- the newly elected Greek government -- as finance minister in the Eurogroup, it was made very clear to me that our country&#39;s democratic process -- our elections -- must not affect the austerity programs that have been implemented in Greece .
At that moment, I thought that there couldn&#39;t be a better justification for Lee Kuan Yew, or the Chinese Communist Party, or some of my rebellious friends who repeatedly told me that if democracy changed anything, it would be abolished.
At this point I would like to present you with an economic model for a real democracy.
I ask you to join me in believing again that Lee Kuan Yew, the Chinese Communist Party and even the Eurogroup are mistaken in believing that we can save on democracy and that we need a real and resilient democracy.
Because without democracy, our societies will be meaner, our futures bleak, and our great new technologies wasted.
On the subject of waste, I would like to point out an interesting contradiction that is currently threatening our economies.
I call it the &quot;twin peaks paradox&quot;.
You know one peak. They know and recognize him as the mountain of debt that casts its long shadow over the US, Europe and the whole world.
We all recognize the mountain of debt
but few recognize his twin.
A mountain of idle cash that belongs to the wealthy savers and corporations who are too afraid to invest it where it would be productive and generate income that would pay off the debt and also produce all the things that the Mankind urgently needs, for example, &quot;green&quot; energy.
I&#39;ll give you two numbers.
In the past 3 months in the US, UK and the Eurozone a total of $3.4 trillion has been invested in all the wealth producing commodities such as industrial plants, machinery, office buildings, schools, roads, railroad tracks, equipment and so on and so on.
$3.4 trillion sounds like a lot of money until you compare it to the $5.1 trillion that was lying around in those same countries and our financial institutions at the same time, doing absolutely nothing but inflating stock markets and house prices to blow up
In this way, debt and unproductive capital form the twin peaks that cannot be balanced out by the usual market mechanisms.
The result is stagnant wages, more than a quarter of 25-54-year-olds in the US, Japan and Europe unemployed, and consequent low aggregate demand, which in a never-ending loop is fueling pessimism among investors who, fearing low demand, promote them themselves by not investing in them. Just like Oedipus&#39; father who, afraid the oracle&#39;s prophecy might come true, that his son would kill him when he grew up,
unintentionally creating the circumstances that lead to Oedipus killing him.
This is my struggle with capitalism --
its exceedingly wasteful ways. All that unproductive capital should be used to improve our lives, to develop human talents and especially to fund all the technologies, &quot;green&quot; technologies, that are crucial to saving the earth.
So is democracy the solution?
I think so. But before we continue, what do we mean by democracy?
Aristotle defined democracy as the form of society in which the free and the poor control the government as a majority.
Athenian democracy, of course, excluded too many --
Women, foreigners, and of course slaves.
However, it would be a mistake to downplay Athenian democracy because of these exclusions.
The essence of Athenian democracy was and is that it included the working poor and not only gave them the right to freedom of expression, but more importantly and crucially, it gave them the right to political participation with equal voting weight in matters of state affairs .
Athenian democracy didn&#39;t last long --
like a candle that shines very brightly, it also burns out quickly.
However, our contemporary liberal democracies do not have their roots in ancient Athens,
but in Magna Carta, in the glorious revolution of 1688, even in the American Constitution.
While Athenian democracy focused on free citizens and empowered the working poor, our liberal democracy is based on the values of Magna Carta, which was ultimately a charter for rulers.
Liberal democracy only emerged when politics and business could be completely separated and the democratic process was limited to politics, while business -- that is, the corporate world -- became a democracy-free zone.
In today&#39;s democracies, from the moment this separation of politics and business began, there has been an unrelenting struggle between the two, with business gradually subverting and disempowering politics.
Do you wonder why politicians aren&#39;t the way they used to be?
It&#39;s not due to a degeneration of their DNA.
It&#39;s because nowadays you can be in government and still not in power because power has migrated from politics to economics and the spheres are separate.
I mentioned my struggles with capitalism.
If you think about it, it&#39;s a bit like a herd of predators that have decimated the animals they feed on so badly that they end up starving to death because of it.
It is similar with the economy, which has cannibalized politics to the point that it is harming itself through the self-inflicted economic crisis. Corporate power is growing, political goods are being devalued, inequality is rising, aggregate demand is falling, and corporate executives are too scared to invest their company&#39;s cash.
The more successfully capitalism expels the &quot;demos&quot; [the people] from democracy, the higher the twin peaks become, and the greater the waste of human labor and of mankind&#39;s wealth.
If that&#39;s true, it&#39;s obvious that we need to bring politics and economics back together, and it would be better if the &quot;demos&quot; remained in control, as in ancient Athens, except for the exclusion of slaves, women, and the Foreigner.
By the way, this is not a new idea.
The Marxist left had this idea 100 years ago and it didn&#39;t end well.
The lesson of the Soviet Union debacle was to be that, without creating new forms of brutality and waste, the working poor would miraculously regain a position like that of ancient Athens.
But there is a solution: Abolish the working poor!
Capitalism does it by replacing low-wage workers with automation and robots.
The problem with this is that as long as economics and politics are separate domains, automation makes the twin peaks higher, the waste loftier, and the social conflicts deeper, just like -- very soon, I think -- in countries like China will come.
So we need to reshape the economy and reunite the realms of economics and politics, while being careful to democratize the reunited realm, or else we&#39;ll end up in a morbid surveillance hyperautocracy that makes The Matrix feel like a documentary.
So the question is not whether capitalism will survive the technological advances it has produced --
the more interesting question is whether capitalism will be replaced by a dystopia akin to that of The Matrix, or something akin to the society of Star Trek, where machines serve humans and humans invest their energies in the exploration of the universe, or indulge in lengthy conversations about the meaning of life in a high-tech version of the ancient Athenian &quot;Agora&quot;.
I think we can be optimistic.
So what would it take, what might it look like to have this &quot;Star Trek&quot;-like utopia instead of the &quot;Matrix&quot;-like dystopia?
In terms of practical implementation, I would like to briefly give you a few examples.
In the corporate realm, please imagine a capital market where you make money while you work and where your capital follows you from one job to another, from one company to the next, and the company -- whichever one you are in currently working -- owned by those currently working at the company.
Then all income comes from capital and from proceeds, and the concept of wage labor is completely obsolete.
No more differentiation between those who own the companies but don&#39;t work in them and employees who work there but don&#39;t own the company. No more tug-of-war between capital and labor, no more large gaps between investment and saving, and ultimately no soaring twin peaks.
In the realm of global political economy: Please briefly imagine that our national currencies had a floating exchange rate, in a universal, global, digital currency managed by the IMF [International Monetary Fund], and the G-20 [Group of 20 largest emerging countries], is issued in the interest of all mankind.
Imagine further that all world trade is traded in this currency -- let&#39;s call it &#39;the cosmos&#39;, in units of &#39;cosmos&#39; -- and each government pays the sum equal to that country&#39;s trade deficit or trade surplus corresponds to a common fund.
Also, imagine this fund investing in &quot;green&quot; technologies, particularly in parts of the world where investment funds are scarce.
This is not a new idea.
It is basically what John Maynard Keynes proposed at the 1944 Bretton Woods Conference.
The problem was that you didn&#39;t have the technical means to implement it at the time.
Today we have them, especially against the background of a reunited politics and economy.
The world I am describing to you is at once libertarian, in which it favors privileged individuals, and Marxist, because it will have buried the separation of capital and labor in the dustbin of history, and Keynesian, globally Keynesian.
But above all else, it&#39;s a world in which we can imagine real democracy.
Will we wake up in such a world
or will we sink into a &quot;Matrix&quot;-like dystopia?
The answer depends on how we decide together politically.
It&#39;s in our hands, and we better do it democratically.
Thanks.
