Roy Price is something most have never heard of, despite the fact that he is likely responsible for 22 mediocre minutes of your life on April 19, 2013.
Probably a very entertaining 22 minutes too, but not for very many of you.
This goes back to the decision Roy made three years ago.
Roy Price is an executive at Amazon Studios,
Amazon&#39;s TV production company.
He&#39;s 47, slim, with a spiky hairstyle and describes himself on Twitter as &quot;movies, TV, tech, tacos.&quot;
Roy has a very important job because he is responsible for choosing the shows and content that Amazon will produce.
Of course, this is a very competitive industry.
There are already so many TV series that Roy can&#39;t pick just one.
He has to find shows that are very, very good.
In other words, he needs to find shows that are on the far right of that curve.
This curve is the rating distribution of over 2500 TV series on the IMDB website. The rating goes from 1 to 10 and the amount shows how many shows received that rating.
If your show scores a nine or higher, it&#39;s a winner.
Then you have a successful show.
It&#39;s shows like Breaking Bad, Game of Thrones, The Wire -- all the addicting shows where after you&#39;ve watched a season your brain is like, &quot;Where are there more of these episodes ?&quot;
That kind of show.
On the left, here at this end, are shows like &quot;Toddlers and Tiaras&quot; -- -- that should tell you enough about what&#39;s going on at this end of the curve.
Roy Price doesn&#39;t worry about going to the left of the curve because I think it takes a lot of intelligence to undercut &quot;Toddlers and Tiaras&quot;.
He&#39;s more concerned with the mean bulge, the average television -- the shows that are neither good nor bad, they just don&#39;t excite.
So he needs to make sure he&#39;s really on the right page.
The pressure is there, and of course it&#39;s Amazon&#39;s first time doing something like this, so Roy Price doesn&#39;t want to take any chances.
He wants to create success.
He needs guaranteed success, so he&#39;s holding a competition.
He takes many TV show ideas and selects eight TV show candidates through evaluation, then produces the first episode of each of those shows and puts them online for anyone to watch for free.
And when Amazon gives stuff away for free, you grab it, right?
Millions of viewers watch these episodes.
However, they don&#39;t know that they are being watched while watching these shows.
They are being watched by Roy and his team, who are recording everything.
They record when you start the show, when you pause, which parts you skip and watch again.
They collect millions of pieces of data and then use that data to decide which show to produce.
Indeed, they collect the data, they process it, and from that comes the answer, and that is, &quot;Amazon should do a sitcom about four Republican US Senators.&quot;
They made this show.
Does anyone know the name of this show?
Yes, &quot;Alpha House&quot;, but it seems that not many can remember this show because it wasn&#39;t that good.
It&#39;s just an average show -- literally -- since the average of that curve is 7.4 and Alpha House comes in at 7.5 -- a little above average, but not exactly what Roy and his team were working towards .
At about the same time at another company, another manager placed a top show through data analysis. His name is Ted, Ted Sarandos, Netflix&#39;s programming manager. Just like Roy, he&#39;s always on a quest to find that one super show, and he uses data to do that, but he does it a little differently.
Instead of running a competition, he and his team looked at existing data on Netflix viewership -- the ratings they give the shows, their history, what shows they like, etc.
Then they use that data to find out these little details about viewers: which shows they like, which producers, which actors.
Once they had all the pieces together, they took a gamble and decided to make a drama series about one senator rather than a sitcom about four senators.
Do you know this show?
Yes, House of Cards. Netflix landed a hit with it, at least for the first two seasons.
&quot;House of Cards&quot; gets a 9.1 rating on this chart. So exactly where they wanted to be.
Of course, the question now is: What happened here?
You have two very competitive, data-savvy companies.
They connect all this data together and it works great for one of them but not for the other company.
Why is that?
Because logic kinda says it should work for everything.
If you collect millions of data for a decision you make, then you should be able to make a good decision.
You have 200 years of statistics as a backup.
It is optimized by very powerful computers.
The least you can expect is good TV, right?
When data analysis doesn&#39;t work that way, it&#39;s a bit scary, because we live in a time where we&#39;re turning more and more to statistics to make serious decisions, well beyond television.
Does anyone here know the company Multi-Health Systems?
No one. Ok, that&#39;s actually good.
Multi-Health Systems is a software company and I hope no one in this room ever comes into contact with that software. If you touch it, you&#39;re in prison.
If someone is in prison here in the US and asks for a release, it is likely that this company&#39;s data analysis will be used to determine whether or not they will be released.
Just like Amazon and Netflix. But instead of deciding if a show will be good or bad, it&#39;s deciding if a person will be good or bad.
Mediocre TV, 22 minutes, that can be really bad, but more years in prison is worse.
Unfortunately, there is evidence that this data analysis, despite the large amount of data
doesn&#39;t always produce the best results. It&#39;s not because a company like Multi-Health Systems doesn&#39;t know how to use data.
Even the most data-savvy companies are sometimes wrong.
Yes, even Google sometimes makes mistakes.
In 2009, Google announced that they could predict outbreaks of influenza, the bad kind, through data analysis -- through data analysis of Google searches.
It worked beautifully and was a huge news sensation. The success culminated in a publication in the magazine &quot;Nature&quot;.
It worked flawlessly, year after year after year, until suddenly it stopped working,
and no one could say why.
It just didn&#39;t work, this again caused a sensation, including the revocation of publication in the magazine &quot;Nature&quot;.
Even the most data-savvy companies like Amazon and Google sometimes get it wrong.
Despite all these flaws, data is increasingly flowing into life&#39;s decisions -- in the workplace, in law enforcement, in medicine.
So we&#39;d better make sure data is helpful.
I also know many difficulties with data. I work in computational genetics -- an area where some very smart people use an unimaginable amount of data to make serious decisions, like deciding on cancer therapy
or the development of a drug. Over the years I&#39;ve seen some patterns in the difference between successful decisions based on data and unsuccessful decisions. This pattern should be spread.
If you ever need to solve a complex problem, do two main things:
First, break this problem down into its individual parts so that you can analyze the individual parts; second, put the pieces back together to make a decision.
Sometimes you have to do this multiple times, but it&#39;s always two things: take apart and put back together.
And now the most important thing: Data and data analysis are only good for the first part.
Data and data analysis, no matter how powerful, can only help to dissect a problem and understand its parts.
You are not suited to putting the pieces back together and then coming to a conclusion.
There is another tool for that and we all have it: our brain.
If there&#39;s one thing the brain is good at, it&#39;s putting pieces and pieces back together even when the information is incomplete and then making a good decision -- especially when it&#39;s an expert&#39;s brain.
That&#39;s why I think Netflix has been so successful, because they&#39;ve used data and reason where they belong in the process.
They use data to better understand their audience, which they otherwise would not have been able to do. But deciding how to take all those pieces, put them back together, and make a show like House of Cards out of it, that wasn&#39;t in the data.
Ted Sarandos and his team made that decision for this show, which meant they took a huge personal risk with that decision.
Amazon, on the other hand, did this in the wrong way.
They used data to drive all of their decisions, first when they competed for TV ideas, then when they chose &quot;Alpha House&quot; as their show.
It was a safe decision because they could always say, &quot;That&#39;s what the data tells us.&quot;
It didn&#39;t lead to the desired result.
Data is helpful for making better decisions, but I believe things go wrong when data starts driving our decisions.
No matter how powerful it is, data is just a tool and not to forget, this device is pretty useful.
Many of you will...
Before there was data, this was the decision-making device.
Many know it.
It is also called &quot;Magic 8 Ball&quot;. It is amazing. For decisions using a yes or no question, all you have to do is shake the ball to get an answer. &quot;Most likely&quot; -- right here, at this very moment.
I&#39;ll fight it out with a tech demo later.
I&#39;ve made quite a few decisions in my life so far that, in hindsight, I should have listened to the ball.
But, of course, as you know, once you have the data available you want to replace it with something much more sophisticated, like data analysis, to make better decisions.
But this does not change the basic structure.
So maybe the ball gets smarter and smarter and smarter. Ultimately, it&#39;s up to us to make decisions if we want to achieve something extraordinary at the end of the right-hand corner.
And I find this to be very encouraging news that despite the vast amount of data, it still pays to make decisions, to be an expert at what you do, and to take risks.
Because in the end, it&#39;s not the data, it&#39;s the risks that get you on the right end of the curve.
Thank you very much.
